\fs28 \cf4 \cb3 Full Site Editing\cb1 \
\cb3 Apr 10, 2025\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 This lesson is the first in a series of exercises to learn how to create block themes, also known as full site editing themes. You will learn about the minimum file requirements, theme setup, and file structure. I will also highlight some differences between classic themes and block themes.\cb1 \
\cb3 By the end of this first lesson, you will have created an 
\f2\b empty
\f1\b0  WordPress block theme with support for the Site Editor. You will continue to build upon this theme over the next lessons:\cb1 \
\cb3 For this lesson, you will need your favorite code editor and a WordPress installation to test your theme.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa398\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs48 \cf2 \cb3 Introduction\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 The {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://fullsiteediting.com/site-creators/introduction-to-the-site-editor/"}}{\fldrslt \cb3 \ul Site Editor}} will be one of your primary tools for creating WordPress block themes. For most block theme projects, this is where you will assemble and style blocks to create your templates, parts, and patterns.\cb1 \
